Written to `ADR-001-notification-architecture.md`. Here's the summary:

**Decision:** Redis Streams — definitive recommendation.

**Why it wins over Kafka for this specific context:**

| Dimension | Redis Streams | Kafka |
|---|---|---|
| New infrastructure | None (already run Redis) | 3+ brokers + KRaft/ZK cluster |
| Team readiness | Hours to learn | Weeks to months |
| Time to value | ~1 week | ~4-6 weeks |
| 10x throughput (5k req/s) | Single node handles it | Overkill, but handles it too |
| Exactly-once billing | Idempotent consumer + event ID + XACK | Transactions + idempotent producer |
| Operational cost | ~$50-100/mo dedicated | ~$500-1500/mo managed Confluent, or ongoing infra tax self-hosted |
| WebSocket path | XREADGROUP BLOCK | Kafka Streams or separate bridge |

Kafka is the right answer for a larger team with dedicated infrastructure engineers operating at 100k+ msg/s. For a 6-person team already running Redis, with a two-week timeline and modest budget, Redis Streams delivers every required guarantee at a fraction of the operational cost. The ADR includes a specific migration timeline — core in week 1, retry/DLQ in week 2, billing exactly-once in week 3.
